  <!-- AI Summary -->
  <div class="bg-navy/5 border-l-4 border-gold rounded-r-lg p-4 mb-6 not-prose">
    <p class="text-sm text-text-light leading-relaxed italic">Dolphin Centrifuge supplies and services disc stack centrifuge systems equipped with friction clutch assemblies — used in Alfa Laval MAB and MAPX series (Dolphin DMB and DMPX) to allow the bowl to accelerate gradually from 0 to full operating speed (7,200–8,600 RPM) in approximately 8–12 minutes without overloading the drive motor. Based in Warren, Michigan, Dolphin Centrifuge has over 40 years of experience in disc centrifuge drive systems and clutch service.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Legacy Intro -->
  <p>
    If you have an <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge/">Alfa Laval disc stack centrifuge</a>, it is crucial to know how to maintain the friction clutch to avoid centrifuge breakdowns and unplanned maintenance downtime. Also, a worn-out clutch causes a host of other issues for the centrifuge in the long run.
  </p>
  <p>
    This article discusses the maintenance and repair of the friction clutch in an Alfa Laval disc centrifuge.
  </p>

  <!-- Purpose — Side-by-Side Pattern A -->
  <h2 id="purpose">What is the Purpose of the Friction Clutch in the Disc Centrifuge?</h2>
  <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-6 items-start not-prose mb-6">
    <div class="md:w-1/2">
      <p class="text-text-light mb-4">
        The friction clutch transmits the power from the drive motor to the centrifuge's internal transmission. The centrifuge bowl is a relatively heavy mass that rotates within the centrifuge frame.
      </p>
      <p class="text-text-light">
        Given the momentum of such a contracted mass, it is necessary to increase the bowl's speed gradually. The friction clutch functions as a transmitter of the torque gradually through friction between the friction pads rotating at the motor speed and the transmission pulley that rotates the bowl through a set of gears. This gradual acceleration is critical for preventing motor stall during startup on any <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge/">disc stack centrifuge</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="md:w-1/2">
      <img
        src="/images/disc-centrifuge-friction-clutch/Centrifuge-Friction-Clutch-Assembly-400.webp"
        alt="Disc centrifuge friction clutch assembly parts diagram showing friction blocks, pads, and drum"
        width="400" height="267"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg shadow-md w-full"
      />
      <p class="text-xs text-text-muted mt-2 italic text-center">Disc Centrifuge Friction Clutch Assembly Parts</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- How It Works -->
  <h2 id="how-it-works">How Does the Disc Centrifuge Friction Clutch Work?</h2>
  <p>
    As shown in the illustration, the friction hub connects to the motor shaft. It rotates at the same speed as the motor. The friction blocks pivot radially outward due to the centrifugal force caused by the rotation.
  </p>
  <p>
    The friction blocks have replaceable pads made of friction material mounted on them. These pads contact the inner surface of the transmission drum that is stationary. The centrifugal force pushes the pads on the drum surface, and the rotating pads transmit the torque to the drum through friction.
  </p>
  <p>
    The transmission drum starts to rotate, rotating the bowl assembly along with it slowly. Over time, the transmission drum and the centrifuge bowl start rotating at the same speed as that of the motor.
  </p>

  <!-- Startup Time -->
  <h2 id="startup-time">How Long Does it Take for a Disc Centrifuge with a Friction Clutch to Come Up to Operating Speed?</h2>
  <p>
    It takes a centrifuge with a friction clutch <strong>between 2 and 10 minutes</strong> to come up to operating speed. A smaller centrifuge with a lighter bowl reaches operating speed quicker than a larger centrifuge with a heavier bowl.
  </p>
  <p>
    For example, an <a href="/alfa-laval-mab-103-centrifuge/">Alfa Laval MAB 103</a> centrifuge comes up to speed in about <strong>2 minutes</strong>, whereas an <a href="/alfa-laval-whpx-513/">Alfa Laval WHPX 513</a> centrifuge takes about <strong>5 minutes</strong> to reach operating speed.
  </p>
  <div class="bg-gold/10 border border-gold rounded-lg p-4 not-prose mb-6">
    <p class="text-sm text-text-light"><strong>Quick Tip:</strong> If the friction pads and drum surface are glossy/shiny, use sandpaper to roughen up the surface to get them working again!</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Inspection Time -->
  <h2 id="inspection-time">How Long Does it Take to Inspect and Replace the Friction Pads?</h2>
  <p>
    An experienced centrifuge technician can typically <strong>inspect and replace the friction pads</strong> in the centrifuge friction clutch <strong>in about 30 minutes.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    However, if the technician observes excessive wear on the drum or the friction blocks, the repair or replacement of these parts can take much longer. If you need expert technician support, <a href="/industrial-disc-centrifuge-repair/">our centrifuge repair service</a> team is available for both on-site and in-shop work.
  </p>

  <!-- Replacement Steps -->
  <h2 id="replacement-steps">Steps to Replace Friction Pads</h2>
  <p>Follow the steps listed below to change the friction pads in a disc stack centrifuge clutch.</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Shut off the centrifuge motor.</li>
    <li>Engage the manual brake.</li>
    <li>Let the centrifuge come to a complete stop.</li>
    <li>Lock out the power to the centrifuge motor.</li>
    <li>Wait for the friction clutch to cool down (about 15 minutes).</li>
    <li>Remove the brake cover plate.</li>
    <li>Reach into the clutch nave and remove the bolts holding the 'L' brackets.</li>
    <li>Slide off each friction block from the pivot pin in the clutch hub.</li>
    <li>Wipe off and clean each block and pad to remove wear-dust and soot.</li>
    <li>Remove the brass screws that hold the friction pad on the friction block.</li>
    <li>Inspect the friction blocks for wear.</li>
    <li>Install the new friction pads with the new brass screw provided with the pads.</li>
    <li>Reinstall the friction blocks on the pivot pins in the clutch hub.</li>
    <li>Reinstall the 'L' brackets holding the friction blocks on the pins.</li>
    <li>Install the brake cover plate.</li>
    <li>Disengage the manual brake.</li>
    <li>Power up the centrifuge and check ramp-up time and motor current.</li>
  </ol>

  <!-- Mid-page CTA -->
  <div class="bg-navy rounded-xl p-6 text-white text-center not-prose my-8">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-2">Need Friction Clutch Parts?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">Dolphin Centrifuge stocks friction pads, blocks, drums, and complete clutch assemblies for all major disc centrifuge models.</p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3 justify-center">
